{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656414"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:14:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:14:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18741"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18741"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.09,0.71,0.04,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11473"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78543"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11473"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18741"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63884"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9907"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26555"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26556"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26915"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78543"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA medical student is studying respiratory physiology and needs to understand the composition of atmospheric air at sea level.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best represents the approximate percentage of oxygen in dry atmospheric air at sea level?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["0.04%","16%","21%","32%","78%"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct composition of dry atmospheric air at sea level includes \u003Cstrong\u003E21%\u003C/strong\u003E oxygen. This relatively constant percentage is maintained through natural processes and is crucial for understanding respiratory physiology.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe other major components of dry atmospheric air include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E78%\u003C/strong\u003E - This is actually the percentage of nitrogen, not oxygen\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E16%\u003C/strong\u003E - This is closer to the percentage of oxygen in expired air after gas exchange\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E32%\u003C/strong\u003E - This is too high and would be toxic if breathed continuously\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E0.04%\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the approximate percentage of carbon dioxide in atmospheric air\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding atmospheric air composition is fundamental for comprehending gas exchange in the lungs, where oxygen diffuses from areas of high concentration (inspired air) to areas of lower concentration (pulmonary capillary blood).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The atmosphere contains approximately 78% nitrogen, 21% oxygen, and 0.04% carbon dioxide at sea level.","Water vapour content in inspired air varies with temperature and humidity but averages around 1-3%.","Noble gases like argon comprise less than 1% of atmospheric air composition."],"references":["Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63884"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18741"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63884","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63884"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T12:47:43+10